    The Gametophytes

   The male gametophyte develops inside the pollen grain. The female gametophyte develops inside
   the ovule. In flowering plants, gametophyte phases are reduced to a few cells dependant for
   their nutrition on the sporophyte phase. This is the reverse of the pattern seen in the
   nonvascular plant groups liverworts, mosses, and hornworts (the Bryophyta).

   Angiosperm male gametophytes have two haploid nuclei (the germ nucleus and tube nucleus)
   contained within the exine of the pollen grain (or microspore).

   Female gametophytes of flowering plants develop within the ovule (megaspore) contained within an
   ovary at the base of the pistil of the flower. There are usually eight (haploid) cells in the
   female gametophyte: a) one egg, two synergids flanking the egg (located at the micropyle end of
   the embryo sac); b) two polar nuclei in the center of the embryo sac; and three antipodal cells
   (at the opposite end of the embryo sac from the egg).

