  Double Fertilization | Back to Top

   The process of pollination being accomplished, the pollen tube grows through the stigma and
   style toward the ovules in the ovary. The germ cell in the pollen grain divides and releases two
   sperm cells which move down the pollen tube. Once the tip of the tube reaches the micropyle end
   of the embryo sac, the tube grows through into the embryo sac through one of the synergids which
   flank the egg. One sperm cell fuses with the egg, producing the zygote which will later develope
   into the next-generation sporophyte. The second sperm fuses with the two polar bodies located in
   the center of the sac, producing the nutritive triploid endosperm tissue that will provide
   energy for the embryo's growth and development.

